title: For Sale:  Glock 26, Gen 3, NIB-X edition! Like new!!
postcontent:
Up for sale is my generation 3 Glock 26. This pistol is the limited "NIB-X edition", so it has the nickel boron coating on top of Glocks standard tennifer on the slide, internals, and barrel. In case you are unfamiliar with nickel boron, it is an ion bonding process that results in a finish that is like stainless steel in appearance, however, it has a lifetime warranty to NEVER chip, crack, or rust. This stuff is near indestructible. I have seen torture test that are unbelievable. People have left guns with this coating in Salt water for 12 months without a single spot of corrosion. They also say you don't have to ever clean or lubricate the gun because the nickel boron has high lubricity. All you ever do is give it a quick wipe and pass a patch down the barrel. However, having said that, this gun has been cleaned regularly anyway.

This pistol is in like new condition. I bought it new and have put only 75 rounds through it. I'm only selling to make room for a new purchase. The pistol comes in the original box, with two magazines. One of the magazines has a finger grip extender that makes drawing and firing much easier. The grip has a rubberized talon decal to help with the grip, but if you don't like it you can remove it. Also comes with the factory speed loader and a nice leather in the waistband holster from Tagua. Let me know if you have any questions, and thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  FMK 9mm model 9C1 Generation 2 NIB 15 Shot 2 Magazines 3 Dot US Made
postcontent:
Our # HGG9C1G2

Photos show a brand new specimen of FMK’s new 9C1 pistol, a distinctive piece that reminds us of several others. Manufacturer is FMK Firearms of Placentia, CA. Type is striker fired, blowback semi-automatic. Construction is steel slide, barrel, and most internal parts mounted in a polymer frame. Slide to frame mating is achieved with integral parts and with a slotted metal trigger insert. This pistol’s slide rails measure at .735 inch on the front and .565 on the back, considerably more metal contacting the slide than many similar pistols, notably the Glock 19. Magazine release is steel as well, not capable of being reversed for southpaws. Trigger is .415 wide combat, with a service width .265 center trigger safety. The 9C1 also has a firing pin safety to guard against accidental discharge if the weapon is dropped. Sight system is conventional 3 dot, with the front sight doubly anchored with a stud and a Phillips screw from the underside. This pistol comes with no fewer than 5 replacement rear sights, for center aim, 1 inch right or left windage, and 2 inch right or left windate. It also comes with a total of two or three, depending on the specimen, front sights for elevation correction. Rear sight is semicircle base slotted into the slide. Barrel is service length 3.87 inch, .562 outer diameter, 1:16 Left Hand Twist 6 groove. Overall length is 6.85 incheas; height is 5.09 inches from the magazine floorplate to the top of the rear sight; weight empty is 23 1/2 ounces with center of gravity empty where the trigger guard intersects the frame. Frame is integrally rail equipped, and grip frame has moderate finger grooves on its front strap, and pliable back strap insert for sure grip and for arresting recoil fatigue. Slide width is 1.07 inches; maximum thickness 1.15 at the slide release lever. Action is full time double action, of course; trigger pull on the photo specimen gauged at a uniform 6 pounds of pressure, with 17 mm travel distance. Magazines are both 14 shot steel body with rounded polymer floorplate and white polymer cartridge follower. The FMK had solid reviews in its 2010 maiden year; since then, the 2nd generation triggers are much improved. Similar pistols command prices upwards of $600 per unit. title: For Sale:  Ak47
postcontent:
This is a nice AK47 Yugo Npap M70. I only put about 200 rounds through it. I love this gun but I don't have a good area to shoot a 30 round magazine. My local ranges have round limits  and I just don't know anyone with large enough property to let me shoot.  This Ak47 is a little bit different than other Ak47s I have seen and shot. The receiver on this gun is thicker, the stock is longer, and there is an extra button to release the dust cover. From research it is because this gun used to have a grenade launcher so the guns were built with that in mind. The receiver is 1.8mm thick. (most ak47s stamped are 1.0mm). When I bought the gun It was missing a retention spring that holds the pins in. I replaced that part with a tapco retainer plate. This makes it easier to get back in then the old style spring. I also put on a bushnell red dot scope. You can read the details on google. I also put a side scope mount on. It's  quick release and it really works well with taking off the red dot to clean the gun then put back on . It's always dead on again! I never had a fail from this gun. Not sure what ak47 does fail. LOL. The gun comes with two magazines- a 30 round steel and  the other one is 40 or 50 round plastic mag.  I never used it. It was given to me by a friend.  I also have 450 rounds of tula 7.62X39 that can go with the gun I have no use for it. I would like to sell in PA. If the gun must be shipped you are responsible for all shipping cost and fees. This gun is like new. Very clean and no scratches.  
I'm asking $600 for just the gun, mags and red dot. If you just want the gun and mags then I will let that go for $525. I would be willing to let the ammo go for $75.

title: For Sale:  Belgium Browning SA-22, .22 LR, Made in Belgium in 1964., Takedown model.
postcontent:
This is a beautiful Grade 1 Belgium Browning SA-22, .22 LR, Made in Belgium in 1964., Takedown model.  This rifle is 95% and is beautiful!  The stock is polished and there is only two small dimples on one side.  There is NO rust, and the blue has only one very small scuff close to the front sight.  Everything else is gorgeous!  This is a VERY collectible rifle!  Item G-35570-1.  Additional photos are available.

The Browning 22 Semi-Auto rifle, also known as the Semi Automatic 22 or SA-22, is a takedown rifle produced by FN Herstal based on a John Browning patent. The rifle is currently produced by Browning as the Semi-Auto 22. Production began in 1914 and continued through 1974 in Belgium and production continued in 1976 in Japan by Miroku.[1] It was first exported by FN for the American market in 1956.  The SA-22 was the first production semiautomatic .22 rifle,[2] and is regarded as a classic firearm.[2][3] It has been offered in several "grades" of engraving and gold inlay, and is a widely collected gun, especially those manufactured in Belgium.

The Semi-auto .22 is a made from blued steel and walnut, and ejects spent cases downward. This feature was intended by the designer to keep the user's face "protected from gasses and flying particles while firing", at which it succeeds.  The lack of a side-mounted ejection port also leaves a large "canvas" for engraving.[2] Factory engraving was done by hand at FN Herstal, and is done by laser engraving with hand finishing at Miroku.

L-3 EOTech XPS3-0 holographic red-dot sight provides rapid heads-up-both-eyes-open target acquisition. Sporting a shortened form factor to save valuable rail space, the XPS3-0 is configured with a Picatinny/Weaver compatible mount.

Because it's powered by a single transverse-mounted CR123A battery, the XPS3 is shorter than the N and AA battery versions - yet it delivers the same parallax-free sighting capabilities. This sight requires a mere 2.75" of rail space, and the battery compartment is raised to accommodate the Delta Ring of most M16/AR15 platform firearms. The battery cap is a simple screw-type cover that's o-ring sealed and tethered to the housing.

The control buttons are positioned on the rear of the rugged aluminum housing for ease of operation. The illuminated reticle is configured with a 65 MOA circle and a single 1 MOA dot - the illumination system provides the operator with 30 brightness levels to choose from, 10 of which are compatible with night vision gear.

Designed for today's modern battlefield; the XPS3-0 is submersible to a depth of 33', and it's repeatable to 2 MOA after remounting. The rear window is a 3/16" thick shatterproof laminate with anti-glare and scratch resistant coatings, and the front lens is 1/8" solid glass. Because the optical system is based upon transmission holography, parallax error is not an issue
